[[File:Oo-jinja (Ichinomiya) torii.JPG|thumb|220px|right|Torii]]

'''Oo Shrine''' (おおじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Yamato-chō Oho|Q126900259|WD=Q126900259|1=Yamato-chō Oho}} (Oho), {{ill|lt=Ichinomiya|Q270810|WD=Q270810|1=Ichinomiya, Aichi}}, {{ill|lt=Aichi Prefecture|Q80434|WD=Q80434|1=Aichi Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} ({{ill|lt=Myojin-taisha|Q9610964|WD=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}}), and its former rank under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=old ranking|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} is {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Enshrined deity ===
The shrine enshrines one {{ill|lt=pillar|Q4817|WD=Q4817|1=Column}}:
* '''{{ill|lt=Kamuyai-mimi-no-Mikoto|Q11588756|WD=Q11588756|1=Kamuyaimimi}}''' (かむやいみみのみこと) - a {{ill|lt=prince|Q12886381|WD=Q12886381|1=Imperial Prince}} of {{ill|lt=Emperor Jimmu|Q200188|WD=Q200188|1=Emperor Jimmu}} (1st emperor), ancestor of the {{ill|lt=Ō clan|Q11430816|WD=Q11430816|1=Ō clan}}.

Some sources say Hachiōji is enshrined in the aiden, which is said to derive from this shrine being called "Tennō-sha" in the {{ill|lt=early modern period|Q5308718|WD=Q5308718|1=Early modern period}}{{Sfn|太神神社（式内社）|1989年}}.

=== History ===
=== Overview ===
Founding is unknown. As seen in both shrine and place names, it is said the {{ill|lt=Ō clan|Q11430816|WD=Q11430816|1=Ō clan}} (Ōuji), who lived here, enshrined their ancestral deity {{ill|lt=Kamuyai-mimi-no-Mikoto|Q11588756|WD=Q11588756|1=Kamuyaimimi}} as clan tutelary deity{{Sfn|太神神社（式内社）|1989年}}. This clan was an ancient lineage based around Oho-gō in {{ill|lt=Tōichi District|Q11405036|WD=Q11405036|1=Toichi district}}, {{ill|lt=Yamato Province|Q907495|WD=Q907495|1=Yamato Province}} (present {{ill|lt=Tawaramoto|Q1203159|WD=Q1203159|1=Tawaramoto, Nara}}, {{ill|lt=Shiki District|Q1155036|WD=Q1155036|1=Shiki District, Nara}}, {{ill|lt=Nara Prefecture|Q131287|WD=Q131287|1=Nara Prefecture}}), where their tutelary {{ill|lt=Ō ni Imasu Mishiritsuhiko Shrine|Q11430652|WD=Q11430652|1=Oonimasumishiritsuhiko Shrine}} (also called Ō Shrine; a Shikinaisha Myojin-taisha) is located.

In the {{ill|lt=Rikkokushi|Q1151168|WD=Q1151168|lt=official histories|1=Rikkokushi}}, in {{ill|lt=Ninju|Q1373077|WD=Q1373077|1=Ninju}} 3 ({{ill|lt=853|Q30367|WD=Q30367|1=853}}) "Ō tenjin" is listed as a myojin, and in the same year was given {{ill|lt=divine rank|Q11591025|WD=Q11591025|1=Shinkai (divine rank)}} Junior Fifth Upper; then in {{ill|lt=Gangyō|Q747451|WD=Q747451|1=Gangyō}} 1 ({{ill|lt=877|Q23905|WD=Q23905|1=877}}), "Ō myojin" was promoted to Senior Fifth Upper{{Sfn|太神神社（式内社）|1989年}}<ref>In '{{ill|lt=Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku|Q1052905|WD=Q1052905|1=Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku}},' Kaśhō 3 (850), 9th month, day 26, "Owari Ō Shrine" appears; a theory identifies this with Oo Shrine, but it is generally identified with {{ill|lt=Atsuta Jingū|Q482065|WD=Q482065|1=Atsuta Shrine}} {{Harv|太神神社（式内社）|1989年}}.</ref>.

Also, in the '{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}' {{ill|lt=Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Jinmyōchō|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} compiled in {{ill|lt=Enchō|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|1=Enchō}} 5 ({{ill|lt=927|Q30470|WD=Q30470|1=927}}), under {{ill|lt=Nakajima District|Q780420|WD=Q780420|1=Nakashima district}}, {{ill|lt=Owari Province|Q514506|WD=Q514506|1=Owari Province}}, it is listed as "Ō Shrine, Myojin-tai," and ranked as {{ill|lt=Myojin-taisha|Q9610964|WD=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}}{{Sfn|太神神社（式内社）|1989年}}. In manuscript copies the name is written both "Ōgami Shrine" and "Ōkamisha," but in that case one "神" character is treated as an interpolation{{Sfn|太神神社（式内社）|1989年}}. In the Engishiki temporary-festival myojin-festival section it also says: "Ō Shrine one seat, alternatively written Ta-sakuta," indicating a form "Ta Shrine." Because the place name "Oho" has long remained in this area, these entries are taken to refer to this shrine{{Sfn|太神神社（式内社）|1989年}}. In the '{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Wamyōshō|1=UNKNOWN}},' this area is identified with Kawasaki-gō, Nakajima District{{Sfn|太神神社（式内社）|1989年}}.

Later details are unclear. It is said to have declined as clan members scattered, and by the {{ill|lt=early modern period|Q5308718|WD=Q5308718|1=Early modern period}} it was called "Tennō-sha"{{Sfn|太神神社（式内社）|1989年}}.

After the {{ill|lt=Meiji Restoration|Q8707|WD=Q8707|1=Meiji Restoration}}, it was ranked {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}} under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}{{Sfn|太神神社（式内社）|1989年}}. Today, its chief priest concurrently serves several shrines, including {{ill|lt=Ōgami Shrine (Ichinomiya)|Q546197|WD=Q546197|lt=Ōgami Shrine|1=Ōmiwa Shrine, Ichinomiya}} in Ichinomiya.

=== Divine ranks ===
; Records of bestowal in the {{ill|lt=Rikkokushi|Q1151168|WD=Q1151168|1=Rikkokushi}} period
* {{ill|lt=Ninju|Q1373077|WD=Q1373077|1=Ninju}} 3 ({{ill|lt=853|Q30367|WD=Q30367|1=853}}) {{ill|lt=June 11|Q2617|WD=Q2617|1=June 11}} - listed as myojin ('{{ill|lt=Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku|Q1052905|WD=Q1052905|1=Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku}}') - written as "Ō tenjin".
* Ninju 3 (853) {{ill|lt=July 12|Q2688|WD=Q2688|1=July 12}} - Junior Fifth Upper ('Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku') - written as "Ō tenjin".
* {{ill|lt=Gangyō|Q747451|WD=Q747451|1=Gangyō}} 1 ({{ill|lt=877|Q23905|WD=Q23905|1=877}}) intercalary {{ill|lt=February 26|Q2359|WD=Q2359|1=February 26}} - promoted from Senior Fifth Lower to Senior Fifth Upper ('{{ill|lt=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Q1052981|WD=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}') - written as "Ō myojin".

; After the Rikkokushi period
* Junior First<ref>[{{NDLDC|991014/413}} 'Jinja Kakuroku, upper volume'] (Kōten Kenkyūjo, 1902, NDL Digital Collection), frame 413.</ref> or Senior Second Upper<ref>{{PDFlink|[https://websv.aichi-pref-library.jp/wahon/pdf/1103283156-001.pdf 'Kokunai Jinmyōchō']}} (copied/combined in Bunsei 13 (1830), Aichi Prefectural Library "Digital Library of Rare Japanese Books"), frame 6.</ref> ('{{ill|lt=Owari Kuninai Jinmyōchō|Q11041830|WD=Q11041830|1=Owari Kokunai Jinmyōchō}}') - written as "Oho Myōjin." Rank differs by manuscript.

